# Auto-push after every change

After completing ANY code change in this project — always:

1. `git add -A`
2. `git commit -F` (write message to a temp file, then use `-F`, since PowerShell doesn't support heredoc)
3. `git pull --rebase origin main` (in case remote has new commits)
4. `git push origin main`

This triggers the GitHub Actions CI/CD pipeline which deploys to production automatically.

**Never leave changes un-pushed.** The user expects to see every change live on the web immediately after it's made.

## PowerShell commit pattern (use this, heredoc doesn't work in PowerShell):

```powershell
# Write message to temp file first
# Then commit with -F flag
git commit -F ".git\COMMIT_MSG_TMP.txt"
```
